Ok so this protocol in @open_ephys_streamer.py is what we would call "PROTOCOL: OFFLINE FILTERING" where the filtering and processing of data is done within the app AFTER the data channels have already been brought into the app. 
:{
1. Frame assembly — background_worker.py:61–84
Each callback() returns one channel block. Blocks are sorted by channel_index and accumulated until 3 are collected (OPEN_EPHYS_EXPECTED_CHANNEL_COUNT), then the complete OpenEphysDataFrame is emitted via signal.

2. Channel processing — open_ephys_streamer.py:47–61
calculate_fields() defines what each channel means:

ch0 & ch1 (lines 50–56): differential subtraction (ch1 - ch0) → bandpass filter → absolute value → the EMG signal
ch2 (lines 58–61): ADC sync line, absolute value only
3. Entry point — main_window.py:559–577
_on_data_received() is where it all comes together:

Line 561–562: reads sample_rate from channel_data_blocks[0]
Line 569: calls received.calculate_fields() to trigger the processing above
Lines 576–578: appends diff_data_block (raw differential), filtered_data_block, and abs_data_block to the rolling display buffers
So the channel-role assignment is implicitly index-based: index 0 and 1 are the two EMG electrodes (differential pair), index 2 is the sync/trigger line. There's no explicit named mapping — it relies entirely on Open Ephys sending channels in order.
}


